ping human-like explanations for complex cognitive processes is challenging due to the abstract nature of these processes. Naive approaches may result in oversimplified or inaccurate explanations, which can undermine trust. Technical challenges include designing a causal reasoning module that can handle the complexity of real-world scenarios and integrating it with existing cognitive modules.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on improving the cognitive capabilities of robots but has not adequately addressed the need for human-like explainability. Existing solutions often rely on post-hoc explanations that lack the depth and clarity required for meaningful human-robot interaction. The integration of causal reasoning into cognitive architectures is a relatively new and complex area of research.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a causal reasoning module that can generate human-like explanations for the robot's actions and decisions. This module will be integrated into the strategic layer of the HARMONIC framework. The methodology will include designing a causal model, training it on a dataset of robot actions and decisions, and evaluating its performance using metrics such as coherence, accuracy, and user satisfaction. The expected outcomes include a more explainable and trustworthy HARMONIC framework that can enhance human-robot collaboration in complex environments.", role='assistant', tool_calls=None, function_call=None, provider_specific_fields=None)'.
